# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The **117th International Olympic Committee Session** was held for the first time in Singapore from 2 to 9 July 2005.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Two important decisions were made through voting during the session – namely the selection of the hosting city for the 2012 Summer Olympics, and a review of the 28 sports currently represented in the summer games.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The session was held at the Raffles City Convention Centre, which is on level 4 of the Raffles City complex.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The opening ceremony on 5 July 2005 was held at the Esplanade – Theatres on the Bay.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] An exhibition was launched at the podium of the Raffles City Shopping Complex, that would continue until 10 July.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The IOC's executive board started two days of meetings.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The executive board meetings resumed with updates on the progress of preparations for the 2006 Winter Olympics in Turin, 2008 Summer Olympics in Beijing and 2010 Winter Olympics in Vancouver by their respective representatives.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The board approved Beijing's request to hold the equestrian events in Hong Kong, which is a separate NOC from mainland China in the "best interests of the competition and the well-being of the horses".
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The opening ceremony was held at the Esplanade - Theatres on the Bay and the guest of honour was the Prime Minister of Singapore, Lee Hsien Loong, who officially opened the session.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] A special type of hybrid orchid had been bred to commemorate the IOC Session in Singapore.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] A cultural performance of dance and songs was held with the theme of "One Voice, One Rhythm, One World".
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Each of the five bid cities had 45 minutes to make a final presentation to the IOC members, after which voting commenced and the final results were announced at 19:30 Singapore time.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The final evaluation report of the 2004 Summer Olympics in Athens was presented and the Athens Games were finally closed.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Reports on the progress of preparations for future Games were also submitted.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The 28 sports in the Summer Olympics programme that existed at that time were all put up on the ballots, three years after a similar attempt failed to gain support from IOC members during the 114th IOC Session in Mexico City.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Prior to the voting, baseball, softball, modern pentathlon, taekwondo and fencing were considered as most likely to be dropped.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Five non-Olympic sports would then be voted to get in, in case any of the existing sports would be dropped, as IOC rules allow a maximum of 28 Summer Olympic sports.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] These sports – golf, roller sports, squash, rugby and karate – were recommended by the IOC Olympic Games Program Committee, which has shortlisted the sports that applied to be included.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Golf and rugby were considered the favorites to be voted in, both mainly for their popularity and also for their relatively small number of events (each one, if accepted, would have consisted of 2 events).
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] A few days before the votes were cast, the IOC accepted the ASOIF request that the number of votes given for each sport will not be published, only "yay" or "nay".
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The reason given for the unusual request was in order to avoid a "popularity ranking" of all Olympic sports.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Any sport that would get a simple majority of "nay" would be dropped from the Olympic program in 2012, but would remain eligible for readmission in future Games.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] In the morning IOC members voted to remove baseball and softball from the games.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The decision has triggered dismay in some nations such as the United States where both sports originated from, and Canada, where both have a strong following.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The main reason for exclusion of softball was that it was included as a women-only sport mainly to be a gender-equalizer bat-and-ball sport for baseball (men-only sport), and with baseball out this reasoning no longer existed.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Another reason given was that both sports consist of large teams and their elimination will make room for many athletes, in comparison to modern pentathlon, for example, which only consist of 64 athletes.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] In the afternoon, a secret vote by IOC members gave squash and karate over 51% of votes, but a subsequent vote to include them in the list of Olympic sports in the Olympic Charter has failed to get the necessary two-thirds majority needed for such amendment.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Therefore, by the end of the day two sports were dropped and none added, and the program of the 2012 Summer Olympics was reduced to 26 sports.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] That night at The Oriental Singapore, then SNOC president and defence minister, Teo Chee Hean threw a banquet.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Rogge gave Singapore full marks for the session organisation, a perfect 6.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Lambis Nikolaou of Greece and Chiharu Igaya from Japan were elected as Vice presidents.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] Singapore's IOC member, Ng Ser Miang was elected to the IOC Executive Board to replace Nikolaou, whose term as board member was due to expire.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The trio who sung the Olympic Hymn in Greek was criticised by both the media and the audience.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] They were Singaporean soprano Khor Ai Ming, Singaporean tenor William Lim and Japanese soprano Satsuki Nagatome.
[src:baseball/117th-ioc-session] The trio sung with gusto just before the announcement of the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The **12–6 curveball** is a type of pitch thrown in baseball.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] It is categorized as a breaking ball because of its downward break.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The 12–6 curveball, unlike the normal curveball (also referred to as the "11 to 5 curve" or a "2 to 8 curve" for its motion), breaks in a downward motion in a straight line.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] This explains the name "12–6", because the break of the pitch refers to the ball breaking from the 12 o'clock position to 6 o'clock on a clock face.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] While the 11–5 and 2–8 variations are very effective pitches, they are less effective than a true 12–6, because the ball will break into the heart of the bat more readily.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The pitch is used throughout Major League Baseball.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] It has several nicknames, including the "yellow hammer" and "drop curveball".
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The 12 to 6 curveball is the toughest type of curveball to hit, because it moves vertically, and has no horizontal break.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The difference of the speed from a fastball and the break make the pitch difficult to hit if a pitcher uses it correctly in a pitching sequence.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The 12 to 6 curveball is usually pitched from the overhand motion, as a three-quarters or sidearm delivery would cause the ball to break 2 to 8 instead of 12 to 6.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The sharp vertical break on the 12–6 curveball is created when pitchers apply topspin to the ball with their fingers in the process of releasing it.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] Depending on the situation and the type of pitcher, the 12–6 curveball may be more or less effective.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The effectiveness of the pitch also depends on the ability of the pitcher to apply topspin to the ball, creating movement.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] When stats for a high level pitcher's average 12 to 6 curveball are factored in, the 12 to 6 and the 11 to 5 are much more effective than Major League Baseball's average throwers of the pitch due to the pitcher's high level of ability for that pitch.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The 12–6 curveball is thrown similarly to most curveballs.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The pitch is generally thrown using a four-seam grip, in which the middle finger on the pitcher's throwing hand is placed in the gap between the two seams on the right side, and the index finger is placed directly next to it.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The pitcher's thumb is placed directly on the bottom of the baseball.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] This grip allows the pitcher to create a high amount of topspin while still having a good control of the pitch.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] The pitch is then thrown with an exaggerated 12–6 motion with both the middle finger and the thumb simultaneously helping move the baseball towards home plate, while the pitcher's index finger giving the ball topspin.
[src:baseball/12-6-curveball] This extensive combination of mechanics makes this one of the most difficult pitches to master.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:baseball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the years 1845 to 1868 throughout the world.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At its December 1868 annual meeting, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) permitted professional clubs.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twelve existing members did "go pro" and constitute the professional field for 1869.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1868 season records for 98 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 15 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors" (not marked), all of the 1869 "pros" (*), all 14 member clubs with at least twelve wins on record, and a few others.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the seven listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At least four Association clubs not listed here would someday try professionalism: Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio (1870); Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana (1871); Middletown of Mansfield, Connecticut (1872); Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey (1873).
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Meanwhile, only two brand new professional baseball clubs would be established in the next three years, the Chicago White Stockings for 1870 and the Boston Red Stockings for 1871.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Their commercial origins may be related to their survival alone by 1877, and on to 2010, while all of their rivals with older and amateur roots fell away.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1867 season records for 89 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 17 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 13 member clubs with at least fourteen wins on record, and a few others.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the nine listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks ten clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Excelsior of Chicago and Buckeye of Cincinnati are listed because they were probably the strongest teams in the west after the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1866 season records for 58 of 93 association members, said to be complete for games between two member clubs.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 20 of that season's teams "major" including three old New York rivals of the Knickerbockers.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 14 members with at least eight wins on record, and a few others.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the fifteen listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks eight clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869, three seasons later.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the preceding 1865 season Marshall Wright lists 30 members with supposedly complete records for most of them.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twenty-two of the thirty were in Greater New York.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 19 teams "major" in the first season that he covers: sixteen of the members and three others (Lowell, Harvard, and Camden).
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] No one traveled much and membership was still depressed by the Civil War.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] There had been 59 delegates at the March 1860 annual meeting, and 55 at the next annual meeting that December (on a new baseball calendar), who thereby intended to play during the 1861 season that the war curtailed.
[src:baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Nine of 59 and eleven of 55 were from outside Greater New York.
[src:baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] The **1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain** was the first, and to date only, professional baseball championship for the national baseball title of Great Britain.
[src:baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] The National League's headquarters were located at 38 Holborn Viaduct, London.
[src:baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] Aston Villa were the National League champions, despite Derby Baseball Club leading the league for much of the season, following their contentious dismissal from the championship, mid-season.
[src:baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] Aston Villa were officially known as Birmingham Baseball Club Limited, with their uniforms emblazoned with 'Birmingham AV' on the jersey, despite being officially part of the famous football club.
[src:baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] As a result, in some reports of the day, they were referred to as Birmingham.
[src:baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] Preston Amateurs were the Amateur League champions, beating Birmingham Amateurs 43–15 and 42–7 in a best of three finals.
[src:baseball/1890-national-league-of-baseball-of-great-britain] A large number of leading football and cricket professionals of the era were involved, alongside American professional baseball players.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The **1919 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the 1919 season.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The 16th edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion Chicago White Sox against the National League (NL) champion Cincinnati Reds.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Although most World Series have been of the best-of-seven format, the 1919 World Series was a best-of-nine series (along with 1903, 1920, and 1921).
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The National Baseball Commission decided to try the best-of-nine format partly to increase popularity of the sport and partly to generate more revenue.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The events of the 1919 World Series are often associated with the Black Sox Scandal, in which several members of the Chicago franchise conspired with gamblers, allegedly led by organized crime figure Arnold Rothstein, to throw the series.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] This led the various franchise owners to install Kenesaw Mountain Landis as the first Commissioner of Baseball in 1920.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] In August 1921, despite being acquitted from criminal charges, eight players from the White Sox were banned from organized baseball for either fixing the series or having knowledge about the fix without alerting the league.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr, another player on the team who was not involved in the scandal, was later suspended after holding out for more pay, but was eventually reinstated.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] They were the first players formally banned in the modern era, and, as it turned out, the template for how Landis would wield his authority throughout his tenure.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] On May 12, 2025, commissioner Rob Manfred lifted all permanent bans — including those of the Black Sox players — on the grounds that deceased players pose no threat to the integrity of the game.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The nine players that were once banned by the MLB (most notably Shoeless Joe Jackson and Eddie Cicotte) are now considered eligible for entry into the Baseball Hall of Fame by as early as 2027.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] In 1919, the Chicago White Sox, who had won the World Series two years earlier, had the best record in the American League (AL).
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Most of the same players had defeated the New York Giants in the 1917 series, four games to two.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] They had fallen to sixth place in the American League in 1918, largely as a result of losing their best player, Shoeless Joe Jackson, and a few other teammates to World War I service.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The team's owner, Charles Comiskey, fired manager Pants Rowland after the season and replaced him with William "Kid" Gleason, who had played over twenty years in the majors but had never managed before.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The 88–52 White Sox won the American League pennant again in 1919, by 3+1⁄2 games over the Cleveland Indians (world champions the following year).
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Jackson was the unquestioned star of the White Sox.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The left fielder hit .351 that season, fourth in the league and in the AL's top five in slugging percentage, RBI, total bases and base hits.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] He was not the only star in a lineup with hardly a weak spot, as former Philadelphia Athletics superstar leadoff hitter Eddie Collins, one of the greatest second basemen of all time, was still going strong in his early thirties, hitting .319 with a .400 on-base percentage.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Right fielder Nemo Leibold hit .302 with 81 runs scored.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] First baseman Chick Gandil hit .290, third baseman Buck Weaver .296, and center fielder Oscar "Hap" Felsch hit .275 and tied Jackson for the team lead in home runs with only seven (as the dead-ball era was coming to a close).
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Even typical "good field, no hit" catcher Ray Schalk hit .282 that year, and shortstop Swede Risberg was not an automatic out with the .256 average and 38 RBI.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Gleason's bench contained two impressive hitters, outfielder Shano Collins and infielder Fred McMullin, both veterans of the 1917 series.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Eddie Cicotte recorded a 29–7 record, leading the league in wins and ranking second in earned run average to Walter Johnson.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Claude "Lefty" Williams finished with a 23–11 record and a 2.64 ERA.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr started 17 games and recorded a 13–7 record with a 2.88 ERA.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Urban "Red" Faber had an 11–9 record with a 3.83 ERA in 20 starts.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Faber was unable to pitch in the series due to illness, leaving manager Kid Gleason with three starting pitchers.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] However, all was not well in the White Sox camp.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] In contrast to the White Sox, the 1919 Cincinnati Reds were upstarts.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] They had finished no higher than third since 1900, and then only twice, before winning the National League (NL) pennant handily in 1919.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The Reds' greatest star was center fielder Edd Roush, who led the league in hitting at .321 and, like the White Sox's Jackson, was in the top five of their respective leagues in most important hitting categories.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Third baseman Heinie Groh was the other great hitter on the team at .310 with a .392 on-base percentage and 79 runs scored.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Slick-fielding first baseman Jake Daubert, a two-time National League batting champion with Brooklyn earlier in the decade, also scored 79 runs and hit .276, while catcher Ivey Wingo hit .273.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The rest of the team was unheralded, including second baseman Morrie Rath, a .264 hitter with no power but a good on-base percentage, and shortstop Larry Kopf, a .270 singles hitter.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The corner outfielders were decidedly weaker hitters, with former Phillies star left fielder Sherry Magee's .215 in 56 games and right fielder Earle "Greasy" Neale's .242 with little power.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] This would prompt Moran to start rookie Pat Duncan in left field in the 1919 series.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] However, the Reds had a strong pitching rotation.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The team's big three included Hod Eller (20–9, 2.39), Dutch Ruether (19–6, 1.82) and Slim Sallee (21–7, 2.06), all among the league leaders in various categories.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] They were backed by three other pitchers who were almost as successful: Jimmy Ring at only 10–9 but 2.26, Ray Fisher at 14–5 and 2.17 with five shutouts, and Cuban Dolf Luque at 10–3 and 2.63, former and future Giant who would win the last game of the 1933 World Series in long relief for New York.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The conspiring players on the White Sox got an unexpected assist when a flu-stricken Faber was left off the World Series roster.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Indeed, years later, catcher Schalk said that had Faber been healthy, there never would have been a fix (since he almost certainly would have gotten starts that went to Cicotte or Williams).
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Despite their many wins on the field, the Sox were an unhappy team.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Many observers blame their attitude on Comiskey's stinginess, despite the fact that the 1919 White Sox payroll was third highest in the AL, behind only Boston and New York.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Stories about the scandal have usually included Comiskey in its gallery of subsidiary villains, focusing in particular on his intentions regarding a clause in Cicotte's contract that would have paid the knuckleballer an additional $10,000 bonus for winning thirty games.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] According to Eliot Asinof's account of the events, *Eight Men Out*, Cicotte was "rested" for the season's final two weeks after reaching his 29th win presumably to deny him the bonus, but the truth may be more complex.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Cicotte won his 29th game on September 19, had an ineffective start on September 24 and was pulled after a few innings in a tuneup on the season's final day, September 28 (three days before the World Series opener).
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] In addition, Cicotte reportedly agreed to the fix the same day he won his 29th game before he could have known of any efforts to deny him a chance to win his 30th.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The story was probably true with regard to the 1917 season, however, when Cicotte won 28 games and hurled the White Sox to the championship.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The first game began at 3 pm at Cincinnati's Redland Field, with 30,511 fans in the stands and ticket scalpers outside the park raking in at least $50 per ticket.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Chicago failed to score in the top of the first.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] In the bottom of the inning, Cicotte (who was paid his $10,000 the night before the series began) took the mound and hit the leadoff hitter (and former teammate), Morrie Rath, in the back with his second pitch, a prearranged signal to Arnold Rothstein that the fix was on.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Even so, the game remained close for a while, due in part to some excellent defense from the conspirators, seeking to deflect suspicion from themselves.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] In the fourth, however, Cicotte "went haywire" (again according to Meany, *op. cit.*), allowing a number of hits in succession climaxed by a two-out triple to the opposing pitcher, as the Reds scored five times to break a 1–1 tie.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Cicotte was relieved at that point, but the damage was done and the Reds went on to add three more runs in later innings and win 9–1.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Sportswriters thought that a bad throw by Cicotte to Risberg in the fourth inning, which prevented a possible double play, was suspicious.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] By that evening, there already were signs that things were going wrong.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Only Cicotte, who had shrewdly demanded his $10,000 in advance, had been paid.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] "Sleepy" Bill Burns and Maharg met with Abe Attell, the former world boxing champ and Rothstein's intermediary, but he withheld the next installment ($20,000) nonetheless to bet on the next game.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The next morning Gandil met Attell and again demanded money, but again to no avail.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Although they had not received their money, the players were still willing to go through with the fix.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] "Lefty" Williams, the starting pitcher in Game 2, was not going to be as obvious as Cicotte.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] After a shaky start, he pitched well until the fourth inning, when he walked three and gave up as many runs.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] After that he became virtually unhittable again, giving up only one more run; but lack of clutch hitting, with Gandil a particularly guilty party, led to a 4–2 White Sox loss.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Attell was still in no mood to pay up afterwards, but Burns managed to get hold of $10,000 and gave it to Gandil, who distributed it among the conspirators.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The teams headed northwest to Comiskey Park in Chicago for Game 3 the next day, with no days off for travel in this Series.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Rookie pitcher Dickey Kerr, the Game 3 starter for the Sox, was not in on the fix.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The original plan was for the conspirators, who disliked Kerr, to lose this game, but by now dissent among the players meant that the plan was in disarray.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Burns still had faith and gathered the last of his resources to bet on Cincinnati.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] It was a decision that would leave him broke, as Chicago scored early—with Gandil himself driving in two runs—and Kerr was masterful, holding the Reds to three hits in a 3–0 complete game shutout.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Cicotte took the mound again for Game 4, and was determined not to look as bad as he had in Game 1.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] For the first four innings, he and Reds pitcher Jimmy Ring matched zeroes.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] With one out in the fifth, Cicotte fielded a slow roller by Pat Duncan but threw wildly to first for a two-base error.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The next man up, Larry Kopf, singled to left; Cicotte cut off the throw from Jackson and fumbled the ball, allowing Duncan to score.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The home crowd was stunned by the veteran pitcher's obvious mistake.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Cicotte then surrendered a double to Greasy Neale which scored Kopf to make it 2–0; this was enough of a lead for Ring, who hurled a three-hit shutout of his own, matching Kerr's in Game 3.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] After the game "Sport" Sullivan came through with $20,000 for the players, which Gandil split equally among Risberg, Felsch, and Williams, who was due to start Game 5 the next day.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Both starters, Williams and Cincinnati's Hod Eller, pitched excellently at first, with neither allowing a runner past first until the top of the sixth, when Eller himself hit a blooper that fell between Felsch and Jackson.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Felsch's throw was offline, sending Eller all the way to third.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Leadoff hitter Morrie Rath then singled over the drawn-in infield, scoring Eller.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Heinie Groh walked before Edd Roush's double—the result of more doubtful defense from Felsch—brought home two more runs, with Roush scoring shortly thereafter.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Eller pitched well enough (he struck out nine batters, including a then-World Series record six in a row, since tied by Moe Drabowsky in the 1966 World Series opener) for the four runs to stand up, and the Reds were only one game away from their first world championship.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The Series reverted to Cincinnati for Game 6.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Dickey Kerr, starting for the White Sox, was less dominant than in Game 3.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Aided by three White Sox errors, the Reds jumped out to a 4–0 lead before Chicago fought back, tying the game at 4–4 in the sixth, which remained the score into extra innings.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] In the top of the tenth, Gandil drove in Weaver to make it 5–4, and Kerr closed it out to record his — and Chicago's — second win.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Despite the rumors already circulating about Cicotte's erratic performances in Games 1 and 4, White Sox manager Kid Gleason showed faith in his ace for Game 7.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] This time, the knuckleballer did not let him down.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Chicago scored early and, for once, it was Cincinnati that committed errors.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The Reds threatened only briefly in the sixth before losing 4–1, and suddenly the Series was relatively close again.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] This marked the only time in World Series history that the winner of Game 7 did not ultimately go on to win the series.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] This did not go unnoticed by Sullivan and Rothstein, who were suddenly worried.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Before the Series started, the Sox had been strong favorites and few doubted they could win two games in a row—presuming that they were *trying* to win.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Rothstein had been too smart to bet on individual games, but had $270,000 riding on Cincinnati to win the Series.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The night before Game 8, Williams—the scheduled starter—was supposedly visited by an associate of Sullivan's known as Harry F.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] He left no doubt that if Williams failed to blow the game in the first inning, he and his wife would be in serious danger.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Chicago wouldn't see another Game 7 for over a century.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Whatever Williams had been told made its impression.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] In the first, throwing nothing but mediocre fastballs, he gave up four straight one-out hits for three runs before Gleason relieved him with "Big" Bill James, who allowed one of Williams' baserunners to score.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] James continued ineffective and, although the Sox rallied in the eighth, the Reds came away with a 10–5 victory for a five-games-to-three Series win.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Jackson hit the only homer of the Series in the third inning after the Reds had built a 5–0 lead.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Immediately after the Series ended, rumors were rife from coast to coast that the games had been thrown.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Journalist Hugh Fullerton of the *Chicago Herald and Examiner*, disgusted by the display of ineptitude with which the White Sox had "thrown" the series, wrote that no World Series should ever be played again.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Jackson led all players with his .375 average.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Some believed that most of his offensive potency came in games that were not fixed and/or when the game seemed out of reach.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] He hit the Series' lone home run in the eighth and final game, a solo shot in the third inning, by which time the Reds were already ahead 5–0.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] His five hits with runners in scoring position came in: Game 6, sixth inning with Kerr pitching; Game 7, first and third innings; Game 8, two in the four-run eighth.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] Shoeless Joe had 12 hits overall, a World Series record at that time and tied for the most in an eight-game series.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The Reds would make their next World Series appearance two decades later, but were swept by the New York Yankees, becoming the last victim of a Yankees dynasty of four straight championships from 1936 to 1939.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] They would win their next championship in 1940 over the Detroit Tigers in seven games after being nine outs away from elimination in Game 7.
[src:baseball/1919-world-series] The scandal cast a shadow that lasted decades.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The **1922 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1922 season.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The 19th edition of the World Series, it matched the National League (NL) champion New York Giants against the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Giants beat the Yankees in five games (four games to zero, with one tie) in the first Series with a permanent best-of-seven format.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] By now, the term "World Series" was being used frequently, as opposed to "World's Series".
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Giants held Babe Ruth in check (he batted only .118 with just one RBI) and scored just enough runs to win each of the games outside the controversial Game 2 tie.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] That game was called on account of darkness, but many thought there was sufficient light to have played some more innings (the sun was still in the sky), and there were some suspicions that one or both teams might have "allowed" the tie to happen to increase the overall gate receipts.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] Commissioner Landis was among those who was dissatisfied with the result.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] One story is that Landis asked Umpire Hildebrand, "Why the Sam Hill did you call the game?" The umpire answered, "There was a temporary haze on the field." The game decision was in the hands of the umpires, but the Commissioner's Office controlled the gate receipts.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] Landis ordered the money, more than $120,000, turned over to World War I charities, thus nullifying any impropriety.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The tied game would turn out to be the third (and final) tied game in the history of the World Series.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The other two tied games occurred in 1907 and 1912.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] No ties are possible under later rules, which allow for suspension of a tied game and resumption of it at a later date, as with Game 5 of the 2008 World Series.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] As of 2024, this is the last time the Giants have won the World Series at home, as their next five championships were all clinched on the road.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] This would prove to be Giants' manager John McGraw's third and final World Series win.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The game and Series remained scoreless until the sixth inning.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] Whitey Witt tripled off of Art Nehf, then was cut down at home trying to score on a fielder's choice, but a Babe Ruth hit got the run home.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees added another run next inning on Aaron Ward's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] A three-run Giant rally in the eighth knocked out Yankee starter Bullet Joe Bush, who allowed four straight leadoff singles, the last of which to Irish Meusel scoring two. and the winning run coming off reliever Waite Hoyt on a Ross Youngs sacrifice fly.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] This was the controversial tie (see above).
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] Pitchers Bob Shawkey and Jesse Barnes went all 10 innings.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Giants scored all three runs in the first on Irish Meusel's three-run home run after two singles.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the first on Wally Pipp's RBI single after Joe Dugan reached second on an error and another run in the fourth on Aaron Ward's home run.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees had tied the game in the eighth on doubles by Babe Ruth and Bob Meusel, but that is the way the game ended.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] Knuckleballer Jack Scott kept the Yankees off the board.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] In the bottom of the third with runners on second and third, Frankie Frisch's sacrifice fly and Irish Meusel's RBI single scored a run each for the Giants, who added an insurance run in the seventh on Frankie Frisch's RBI single.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] This contest moved along even faster than Game 3.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] It was over in a snappy 1:41, with Giants pitcher Hugh McQuillan going the distance for a 4-3 win.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored two runs in the first on back-to-back singles by Wally Pipp and Bob Meusel, but in the fifth after a leadoff single and double, Dave Bancroft's two-run single tied the game.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] After a single and groundout, Irish Meusel's groundout and Ross Youngs's RBI single scored a run each.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] Aaron Ward's home run in the seventh cut the Giants' lead to one, but the Yankees did not score after that.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] Art Nehf's five-hit pitching combined with a three-run eighth inning won the Series for the Giants.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees scored a run in the first when Joe Dugan singled with one out, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Wally Pipp's RBI single, but in the bottom of the second with runners on second and third, Bill Cunningham's two-run single gave the Giants the lead.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Yankees tied the game in the fifth on Bullet Joe Bush's RBI single after a walk and single, then took the lead on Everett Scott's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The decisive rally began with a Heinie Groh single and Frankie Frisch double.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] After an intentional walk to Ross Youngs, a two-run single by High Pockets Kelly put the Giants on top.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The next batter, Lee King, inserted in the outfield that inning for defensive purposes, delivered an RBI single to make it 5-3, and that's how it ended.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] This was the second of three consecutive matchups between the Yankees and Giants (1921–1923) marked the only time (as of 2023), that three straight World Series featured the same two clubs.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] Brothers Bob and Irish Meusel played against each other in each of those three series, making them the first set of brothers to play against each other on opposing teams in a World Series or any Big Four championship series.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] The Giants became the second NL team to win back-to-back World Series, following the Chicago Cubs in 1907–08, and remained the last until the 1975–76 Cincinnati Reds.
[src:baseball/1922-world-series] This also remains the last World Series to be won by the Giants at home, as their championships of 1933 and 1954 (for New York) and 2010, 2012 and 2014 (for San Francisco) were all clinched as the visiting team.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The initial objective of the batting team is to have a player reach first base safely; this occurs either when the batter hits the ball and reaches first base before an opponent retrieves the ball and touches the base, or when the pitcher persists in throwing the ball out of the batter's reach.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Players on the batting team who reach first base without being called "out" can attempt to advance to subsequent bases as a runner, either immediately or during teammates' turns batting.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The fielding team tries to prevent runs by using the ball to get batters or runners "out", which forces them out of the field of play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The pitcher can get the batter out by throwing three pitches which result in strikes, while fielders can get the batter out by catching a batted ball before it touches the ground, and can get a runner out by tagging them with the ball while the runner is not touching a base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The opposing teams switch back and forth between batting and fielding; the batting team's turn to bat is over once the fielding team records three outs.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] One turn batting for each team constitutes an inning.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A game is usually composed of nine innings, and the team with the greater number of runs at the end of the game wins.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Most games end after the ninth inning, but if scores are tied at that point, extra innings are usually played.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Baseball has no game clock, though some competitions feature pace-of-play regulations such as a pitch clock to shorten game time.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Baseball evolved from older bat-and-ball games already being played in England by the mid-18th century.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] This game was brought by immigrants to North America, where the modern version developed.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In addition to North America, baseball spread throughout the rest of the Americas and the Asia–Pacific in the 19th and 20th centuries, and is now considered the most popular sport in parts of Central and South America, the Caribbean, and East Asia, particularly in Japan, South Korea, and Taiwan.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In Major League Baseball (MLB), the highest level of professional baseball in the United States and Canada, teams are divided into the National League (NL) and American League (AL), each with three divisions: East, West, and Central.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The MLB champion is determined by playoffs that culminate in the World Series.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The top level of play is similarly split in Japan between the Central and Pacific Leagues and in Cuba between the West League and East League.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The World Baseball Classic, organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation, is the major international competition of the sport and attracts the top national teams from around the world.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Baseball was played at the Olympic Games from 1992 to 2008, and was reinstated on a one-off basis in 2020.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A baseball game is played between two teams, each composed of nine players, that take turns playing offense (batting and baserunning) and defense (pitching and fielding).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A pair of turns, one at bat and one in the field, by each team constitutes an inning.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A game consists of nine innings (seven innings at the high school level and in doubleheaders in college and Minor League Baseball; and six innings at the Little League level).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] One team—customarily the visiting team—bats in the top, or first half, of every inning.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The other team—customarily the home team—bats in the bottom, or second half, of every inning.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The goal of the game is to score more points (runs) than the other team.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The players on the team at bat attempt to score runs by touching all four bases, in order, set at the corners of the square-shaped baseball diamond.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A player bats at home plate and must attempt to safely reach a base before proceeding, counterclockwise, from first base, to second base, third base, and back home to score a run.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The team in the field attempts to prevent runs from scoring by recording outs, which remove opposing players from offensive action until their next turn at bat comes up again.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] When three outs are recorded, the teams switch roles for the next half-inning.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If the score of the game is tied after nine innings, extra innings are played to resolve the contest.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Many amateur games, particularly unorganized ones, involve different numbers of players and innings.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The game is played on a field whose primary boundaries, the foul lines, extend forward from home plate at 45-degree angles.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The 90-degree area within the foul lines is referred to as fair territory; the 270-degree area outside them is foul territory.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The part of the field enclosed by the bases and several yards beyond them is the infield; the area farther beyond the infield is the outfield.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In the middle of the infield is a raised pitcher's mound, with a rectangular rubber plate (the rubber) at its center.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The outer boundary of the outfield is typically demarcated by a raised fence, which may be of any material and height.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The fair territory between home plate and the outfield boundary is baseball's field of play, though significant events can take place in foul territory, as well.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Protective helmets are also standard equipment for all batters.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] At the beginning of each half-inning, the nine players of the fielding team arrange themselves around the field.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] One of them, the pitcher, stands on the pitcher's mound.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The pitcher begins the pitching delivery with one foot on the rubber, pushing off it to gain velocity when throwing toward home plate.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Another fielding team player, the catcher, squats on the far side of home plate, facing the pitcher.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The rest of the fielding team faces home plate, typically arranged as four infielders—who set up along or within a few yards outside the imaginary lines (basepaths) between first, second, and third base—and three outfielders.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In the standard arrangement, there is a first baseman positioned several steps to the left of first base, a second baseman to the right of second base, a shortstop to the left of second base, and a third baseman to the right of third base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The basic outfield positions are left fielder, center fielder, and right fielder.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] With the exception of the catcher, all fielders are required to be in fair territory when the pitch is delivered.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A neutral umpire sets up behind the catcher.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Other umpires will be distributed around the field as well.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Play starts with a member of the batting team, the batter, standing in either of the two batter's boxes next to home plate, holding a bat.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The batter waits for the pitcher to throw a pitch (the ball) toward home plate, and attempts to hit the ball with the bat.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The catcher catches pitches that the batter does not hit—as a result of either electing not to swing or failing to connect—and returns them to the pitcher.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A batter who hits the ball into the field of play must drop the bat and begin running toward first base, at which point the player is referred to as a *runner* (or, until the play is over, a *batter-runner*).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A batter-runner who reaches first base without being put out is said to be *safe* and is on base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A batter-runner may choose to remain at first base or attempt to advance to second base or even beyond—however far the player believes can be reached safely.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base despite proper play by the fielders has recorded a hit.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A player who reaches first base safely on a hit is credited with a single.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If a player makes it to second base safely as a direct result of a hit, it is a double; third base, a triple.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air within the foul lines over the entire outfield (and outfield fence, if there is one), or if the batter-runner otherwise safely circles all the bases, it is a home run: the batter and any runners on base may all freely circle the bases, each scoring a run.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] This is the most desirable result for the batter.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The ultimate and most desirable result possible for a batter would be to hit a home run while all three bases are occupied or "loaded", thus scoring four runs on a single hit.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A player who reaches base due to a fielding mistake is not credited with a hit—instead, the responsible fielder is charged with an error.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Any runners already on base may attempt to advance on batted balls that land, or contact the ground, in fair territory, before or after the ball lands.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A runner on first base *must* attempt to advance if a ball lands in play, as only one runner may occupy a base at any given time; the same applies for other runners if they are on a base that a teammate is forced to advance to.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If a ball hit into play rolls foul before passing through the infield, it becomes dead and any runners must return to the base they occupied when the play began.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If the ball is hit in the air and caught before it lands, the batter has flied out and any runners on base may attempt to advance only if they tag up (contact the base they occupied when the play began, as or after the ball is caught).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Runners may also attempt to advance to the next base while the pitcher is in the process of delivering the ball to home plate; a successful effort is a stolen base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A pitch that is not hit into the field of play is called either a strike or a ball.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A batter against whom three strikes are recorded strikes out.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A batter against whom four balls are recorded is awarded a base on balls or walk, a free advance to first base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While the team at bat is trying to score runs, the team in the field is attempting to record outs.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In addition to the strikeout and flyout, common ways a member of the batting team may be put out include the ground out, force out, and tag out.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] These occur either when a runner is forced to advance to a base, and a fielder with possession of the ball reaches that base before the runner does, or the runner is touched by the ball, held in a fielder's hand, while not on a base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] (The batter-runner is always forced to advance to first base, and any other runners must advance to the next base if a teammate is forced to advance to their base.) It is possible to record two outs in the course of the same play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Three outs in one play, a triple play, is possible, though rare.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Players put out or retired must leave the field, returning to their team's dugout or bench.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A runner may be stranded on base when a third out is recorded against another player on the team.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Stranded runners do not benefit the team in its next turn at bat as every half-inning begins with the bases empty.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] An individual player's turn batting or plate appearance is complete when the player reaches base, hits a home run, makes an out, or hits a ball that results in the team's third out, even if it is recorded against a teammate.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] On rare occasions, a batter may be at the plate when, without the batter's hitting the ball, a third out is recorded against a teammate—for instance, a runner getting caught stealing (tagged out attempting to steal a base).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A batter with this sort of incomplete plate appearance starts off the team's next turn batting; any balls or strikes recorded against the batter the previous inning are erased.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A runner may circle the bases only once per plate appearance and thus can score at most a single run per batting turn.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Once a player has completed a plate appearance, that player may not bat again until the eight other members of the player's team have all taken their turn at bat in the batting order.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The batting order is set before the game begins, and may not be altered except for substitutions.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Once a player has been removed for a substitute, that player may not reenter the game.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Children's games often have more lenient rules, such as Little League rules, which allow players to be substituted back into the same game.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If the designated hitter (DH) rule is in effect, each team has a tenth player whose sole responsibility is to bat (and run).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The DH takes the place of another player—almost invariably the pitcher—in the batting order, but does not field.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Thus, even with the DH, each team still has a batting order of nine players and a fielding arrangement of nine players.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The number of players on a baseball roster, or *squad*, varies by league and by the level of organized play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A Major League Baseball (MLB) team has a roster of 26 players with specific roles.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Most baseball leagues worldwide have the DH rule, including MLB, Japan's Pacific League, and Caribbean professional leagues, along with major American amateur organizations.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The Central League in Japan does not have the rule and high-level minor league clubs connected to National League teams are not required to field a DH.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In leagues that apply the designated hitter rule, a typical team has nine offensive regulars (including the DH), five starting pitchers, seven or eight relievers, a backup catcher, and two or three other reserve players.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The manager, or head coach, oversees the team's major strategic decisions, such as establishing the starting rotation, setting the lineup, or batting order, before each game, and making substitutions during games—in particular, bringing in relief pitchers.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Managers are typically assisted by two or more coaches; they may have specialized responsibilities, such as working with players on hitting, fielding, pitching, or strength and conditioning.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] At most levels of organized play, two coaches are stationed on the field when the team is at bat: the first base coach and third base coach, who occupy designated coaches' boxes, just outside the foul lines.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] These coaches assist in the direction of baserunners, when the ball is in play, and relay tactical signals from the manager to batters and runners, during pauses in play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In contrast to many other team sports, baseball managers and coaches generally wear their team's uniforms; coaches must be in uniform to be allowed on the field to confer with players during a game.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Any baseball game involves one or more umpires, who make rulings on the outcome of each play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] At a minimum, one umpire will stand behind the catcher, to have a good view of the strike zone, and call balls and strikes.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Additional umpires may be stationed near the other bases, thus making it easier to judge plays such as attempted force outs and tag outs.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In MLB, four umpires are used for each game, one near each base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In the playoffs, six umpires are used: one at each base and two in the outfield along the foul lines.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Many of the pre-game and in-game strategic decisions in baseball revolve around a fundamental fact: in general, right-handed batters tend to be more successful against left-handed pitchers and, to an even greater degree, left-handed batters tend to be more successful against right-handed pitchers.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A manager with several left-handed batters in the regular lineup, who knows the team will be facing a left-handed starting pitcher, may respond by starting one or more of the right-handed backups on the team's roster.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] During the late innings of a game, as relief pitchers and pinch hitters are brought in, the opposing managers will often go back and forth trying to create favorable matchups with their substitutions.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The manager of the fielding team trying to arrange same-handed pitcher-batter matchups and the manager of the batting team trying to arrange opposite-handed matchups.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] With a team that has the lead in the late innings, a manager may remove a starting position player—especially one whose turn at bat is not likely to come up again—for a more skillful fielder (known as a defensive substitution).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The tactical decision that precedes almost every play in a baseball game involves pitch selection.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] By gripping and then releasing the baseball in a certain manner, and by throwing it at a certain speed, pitchers can cause the baseball to break to either side, or downward, as it approaches the batter, thus creating differing pitches that can be selected.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Among the resulting wide variety of pitches that may be thrown, the four basic types are the fastball, the changeup (or off-speed pitch), and two breaking balls—the curveball and the slider.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Pitchers have different repertoires of pitches they are skillful at throwing.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Conventionally, before each pitch, the catcher signals the pitcher what type of pitch to throw, as well as its general vertical or horizontal location.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If there is disagreement on the selection, the pitcher may shake off the sign and the catcher will call for a different pitch.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] With a runner on base and taking a lead, the pitcher may attempt a pickoff, a quick throw to a fielder covering the base to keep the runner's lead in check or, optimally, effect a tag out.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Pickoff attempts, however, are subject to rules that severely restrict the pitcher's movements before and during the pickoff attempt.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Violation of any one of these rules could result in the umpire calling a balk against the pitcher, which permits any runners on base to advance one base with impunity.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If an attempted stolen base is anticipated, the catcher may call for a pitchout, a ball thrown deliberately off the plate, allowing the catcher to catch it while standing and throw quickly to a base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Facing a batter with a strong tendency to hit to one side of the field, the fielding team may employ a shift, with most or all of the fielders moving to the left or right of their usual positions.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] With a runner on third base, the infielders may play in, moving closer to home plate to improve the odds of throwing out the runner on a ground ball, though a sharply hit grounder is more likely to carry through a drawn-in infield.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Several basic offensive tactics come into play with a runner on first base, including the fundamental choice of whether to attempt a steal of second base.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The hit and run is sometimes employed, with a skillful contact hitter, the runner takes off with the pitch, drawing the shortstop or second baseman over to second base, creating a gap in the infield for the batter to poke the ball through.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The sacrifice bunt, calls for the batter to focus on making soft contact with the ball, so that it rolls a short distance into the infield, allowing the runner to advance into scoring position as the batter is thrown out at first.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A batter, particularly one who is a fast runner, may also attempt to bunt for a hit.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A sacrifice bunt employed with a runner on third base, aimed at bringing that runner home, is known as a squeeze play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] With a runner on third and fewer than two outs, a batter may instead concentrate on hitting a fly ball that, even if it is caught, will be deep enough to allow the runner to tag up and score—a successful batter, in this case, gets credit for a sacrifice fly.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In order to increase the chance of advancing a batter to first base via a walk, the manager will sometimes signal a batter who is ahead in the count (i.e., has more balls than strikes) to take, or not swing at, the next pitch.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The batter's potential reward of reaching base (via a walk) exceeds the disadvantage if the next pitch is a strike.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Consensus once held that today's baseball is a North American development from the older game rounders, popular among children in Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] American baseball historian David Block suggests that the game originated in England; recently uncovered historical evidence supports this position.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] According to Block and official MLB historian John Thorn, this earlier version of baseball may have involved hitting the ball with a hand, making it akin to today's punchball.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Block argues that rounders and early baseball were actually regional variants of each other, and that the game's most direct antecedents are the English games of stoolball and "tut-ball".
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The earliest known reference to baseball is in a 1744 British publication, *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book*, by John Newbery.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Block discovered that the first recorded game of "Base Ball" took place in 1749 in Surrey, and featured the Prince of Wales as a player.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] This early form of the game was apparently brought to Canada by English immigrants.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] By the early 1830s, there were reports of a variety of uncodified bat-and-ball games recognizable as early forms of baseball being played around North America.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The first recorded baseball game in North America was played in Beachville, Ontario, Canada, on June 4, 1838.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1845, Alexander Cartwright, a member of New York City's Knickerbocker Club, led the codification of the so-called Knickerbocker Rules, which in turn were based on rules developed in 1837 by William R.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While there are reports that the New York Knickerbockers played games in 1845, the contest long recognized as the first recorded baseball game in U.S. history took place on June 19, 1846, in Hoboken, New Jersey: the "New York Nine" defeated the Knickerbockers, 23–1, in four innings.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] With the Knickerbocker code as the basis, the rules of modern baseball continued to evolve over the next half-century.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The game then went on to spread throughout the Pacific Rim and the Americas, with Americans backing the sport as a way to spread American values.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In the mid-1850s, a baseball craze hit the New York metropolitan area, and by 1856, local journals were referring to baseball as the "national pastime" or "national game".
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A year later, the sport's first governing body, the National Association of Base Ball Players, was formed.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1867, it barred participation by African Americans.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The more formally structured National League was founded in 1876.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Professional Negro leagues formed, but quickly folded.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1887, softball, under the name of indoor baseball or indoor-outdoor, was invented as a winter version of the parent game.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The American League evolved from the minor Western League, which was reorganized under Ban Johnson in 1893.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] It was not until 1901 that the American League was formally established as a major league.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] By 1893, crucial structural changes (like moving the pitching distance to 60 feet, 6 inches) firmly cemented the modern rulebook.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The National Agreement of 1903 formalized relations both between the two major leagues and between them and the National Association of Professional Base Ball Leagues, representing most of the country's minor professional leagues.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The World Series, pitting the two major league champions against each other, was inaugurated that fall.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series led to the formation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The first commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, was elected in 1920.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] That year also saw the founding of the Negro National League; the first significant Negro league, it would operate until 1931.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] For part of the 1920s, it was joined by the Eastern Colored League.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Compared with the present, professional baseball in the early 20th century was lower-scoring, and pitchers were more dominant.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] This so-called "dead-ball era" ended in the early 1920s with several changes in rule and circumstance that were advantageous to hitters.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Strict new regulations that governed the ball's size, shape and composition, along with a new rule officially banning the spitball and other pitches that depended on the ball being treated or roughed-up with foreign substances, resulted in a ball that traveled farther when hit.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The rise of the legendary player Babe Ruth, the first great power hitter of the new era, helped permanently alter the nature of the game.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Louis Cardinals general manager Branch Rickey invested in several minor league clubs and developed the first modern farm system.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A new Negro National League was organized in 1933; four years later, it was joined by the Negro American League.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The first elections to the National Baseball Hall of Fame took place in 1936.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1939, Little League Baseball was founded in Pennsylvania.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Many minor league teams disbanded when World War II led to a player shortage.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Wrigley led the formation of the All-American Girls Professional Baseball League to help keep the game in the public eye.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The first crack in the unwritten agreement barring blacks from white-controlled professional ball occurred in 1945: Jackie Robinson was signed by the National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and began playing for their minor league team in Montreal.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1947, Robinson broke the major leagues' color barrier when he debuted with the Dodgers.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Latin-American players, largely overlooked before, also started entering the majors in greater numbers.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1951, two Chicago White Sox, Venezuelan-born Chico Carrasquel and black Cuban-born Minnie Miñoso, became the first Hispanic All-Stars.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Integration proceeded slowly: by 1953, only six of the 16 major league teams had a black player on the roster.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1975, the union's power—and players' salaries—began to increase greatly when the reserve clause was effectively struck down, leading to the free agency system.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Significant work stoppages occurred in 1981 and 1994, the latter forcing the cancellation of the World Series for the first time in 90 years.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Attendance had been growing steadily since the mid-1970s and in 1994, before the stoppage, the majors were setting their all-time record for per-game attendance.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] After play resumed in 1995, non-division-winning wild card teams became a permanent fixture of the post-season.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Regular-season interleague play was introduced in 1997 and the second-highest attendance mark for a full season was set.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 2000, the National and American Leagues were dissolved as legal entities.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While their identities were maintained for scheduling purposes (and the designated hitter distinction), the regulations and other functions—such as player discipline and umpire supervision—they had administered separately were consolidated under the rubric of MLB.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 2001, Barry Bonds established the current record of 73 home runs in a single season.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 2007, Bonds became MLB's all-time home run leader, surpassing Hank Aaron, as total major league and minor league attendance both reached all-time highs.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Despite having been called "America's national pastime", baseball is well-established in several other countries.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] As early as 1877, a professional league, the International Association, featured teams from both Canada and the United States.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While baseball is widely played in Canada and many minor league teams have been based in the country, the American major leagues did not include a Canadian club until 1969, when the Montreal Expos joined the National League as an expansion team.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1977, the expansion Toronto Blue Jays joined the American League.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1847, American soldiers played what may have been the first baseball game in Mexico at Parque Los Berros in Xalapa, Veracruz.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The first formal baseball league outside of the United States and Canada was founded in 1878 in Cuba, which maintains a rich baseball tradition.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The English football club, Aston Villa, were the first British baseball champions winning the 1890 National League of Baseball of Great Britain.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The 2025 National Champions were the London Mets.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The Dominican Republic held its first islandwide championship tournament in 1912.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Professional baseball tournaments and leagues began to form in other countries between the world wars, including the Netherlands (formed in 1922), Australia (1934), Japan (1936), Mexico (1937), and Puerto Rico (1938).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The Japanese major leagues have long been considered the highest quality professional circuits outside of the United States.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] After World War II, professional leagues were founded in many Latin American countries, most prominently Venezuela (1946) and the Dominican Republic (1955).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Since the early 1970s, the annual Caribbean Series has matched the championship clubs from the four leading Latin American winter leagues: the Dominican Professional Baseball League, Mexican Pacific League, Puerto Rican Professional Baseball League, and Venezuelan Professional Baseball League.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In Asia, South Korea (1982), Taiwan (1990) and China (2003) all have professional leagues.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Other European countries have seen professional leagues; the most successful, other than the Dutch league, is the Italian league, founded in 1948.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 2004, Australia won a surprise silver medal at the Olympic Games.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The Confédération Européene de Baseball (European Baseball Confederation), founded in 1953, organizes a number of competitions between clubs from different countries.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Women's baseball is played on an organized amateur basis in numerous countries.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] After being admitted to the Olympics as a medal sport beginning with the 1992 Games, baseball was dropped from the 2012 Summer Olympic Games at the 2005 International Olympic Committee meeting.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While the sport's lack of a following in much of the world was a factor, more important was MLB's reluctance to allow its players to participate during the major league season.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] MLB initiated the World Baseball Classic, scheduled to precede its season, partly as a replacement, high-profile international tournament.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The inaugural Classic, held in March 2006, was the first tournament involving national teams to feature a significant number of MLB participants.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The Baseball World Cup was discontinued after its 2011 edition in favor of an expanded World Baseball Classic.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Baseball has certain attributes that set it apart from the other popular team sports in the countries where it has a following.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] All of these sports use a clock, play is less individual, and the variation between playing fields is not as substantial or important.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The comparison between cricket and baseball demonstrates that many of baseball's distinctive elements are shared in various ways with similar sports.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In clock-limited sports, games often end with a team that holds the lead killing the clock rather than competing aggressively against the opposing team.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In contrast, baseball has no clock, thus a team cannot win without getting the last batter out and rallies are not constrained by time.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] At almost any turn in any baseball game, the most advantageous strategy is some form of aggressive strategy.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While nine innings has been the standard since the beginning of professional baseball, the duration of the average major league game has increased steadily through the years.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] At the turn of the 20th century, games typically took an hour and a half to play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In the 1920s, they averaged just less than two hours, which eventually ballooned to 2:38 in 1960.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] By 1997, the average American League game lasted 2:57 (National League games were about 10 minutes shorter—pitchers at the plate making for quicker outs than designated hitters).
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 2004, Major League Baseball declared that its goal was an average game of 2:45.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] By 2014, though, the average MLB game took over three hours to complete.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The lengthening of games is attributed to longer breaks between half-innings for television commercials, increased offense, more pitching changes, and a slower pace of play, with pitchers taking more time between each delivery, and batters stepping out of the box more frequently.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Other leagues have experienced similar issues.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 2008, Nippon Professional Baseball took steps aimed at shortening games by 12 minutes from the preceding decade's average of 3:18.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 2016, the average nine-inning playoff game in Major League baseball was 3 hours and 35 minutes.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] This was up 10 minutes from 2015 and 21 minutes from 2014.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In response to the lengthening of the game, MLB decided from the 2023 season onward to institute a pitch clock rule to penalize batters and pitchers who take too much time between pitches; this had the effect of shortening 2023 regular season games by 24 minutes on average.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Although baseball is a team sport, individual players are often placed under scrutiny and pressure.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While rewarding, it has sometimes been described as "ruthless" due to the pressure on the individual player.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] In 1915, a baseball instructional manual pointed out that every single pitch, of which there are often more than two hundred in a game, involves an individual, one-on-one contest: "the pitcher and the batter in a battle of wits".
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Pitcher, batter, and fielder all act essentially independent of each other.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While coaching staffs can signal pitcher or batter to pursue certain tactics, the execution of the play itself is a series of solitary acts.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] If the batter hits a line drive, the outfielder is solely responsible for deciding to try to catch it or play it on the bounce and for succeeding or failing.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The statistical precision of baseball is both facilitated by this isolation and reinforces it.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] There is no statistical equivalent in cricket for the fielding error and thus less emphasis on personal responsibility in this area of play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Unlike those of most sports, baseball playing fields can vary significantly in size and shape.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Major league teams often skirt even this rule.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] For example, at Daikin Park, which became the home of the Houston Astros in 2000, the Crawford Boxes in left field are only 315 feet (96 m) from home plate.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] There are no rules at all that address the height of fences or other structures at the edge of the outfield.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The most famously idiosyncratic outfield boundary is the left-field wall at Boston's Fenway Park, in use since 1912: the Green Monster is 310 feet (94 m) from home plate down the line and 37 feet (11 m) tall.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Similarly, there are no regulations at all concerning the dimensions of foul territory.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Thus a foul fly ball may be entirely out of play in a park with little space between the foul lines and the stands, but a foulout in a park with more expansive foul ground.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A fence in foul territory that is close to the outfield line will tend to direct balls that strike it back toward the fielders, while one that is farther away may actually prompt more collisions, as outfielders run full speed to field balls deep in the corner.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] These variations can make the difference between a double and a triple or inside-the-park home run.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The surface of the field is also unregulated.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While the adjacent image shows a traditional field surfacing arrangement (and the one used by virtually all MLB teams with naturally surfaced fields), teams are free to decide what areas will be grassed or bare.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Some fields—including several in MLB—use artificial turf.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Surface variations can have a significant effect on how ground balls behave and are fielded as well as on baserunning.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Similarly, the presence of a roof (seven major league teams play in stadiums with permanent or retractable roofs) can greatly affect how fly balls are played.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] While football and soccer players deal with similar variations of field surface and stadium covering, the size and shape of their fields are much more standardized.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The area out-of-bounds on a football or soccer field does not affect play the way foul territory in baseball does, so variations in that regard are largely insignificant.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] These physical variations create a distinctive set of playing conditions at each ballpark.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Other local factors, such as altitude and climate, can also significantly affect play.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A given stadium may acquire a reputation as a pitcher's park or a hitter's park, if one or the other discipline notably benefits from its unique mix of elements.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The most exceptional park in this regard is Coors Field, home of the Colorado Rockies.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Its high altitude—5,282 feet (1,610 m) above sea level—is partly responsible for giving it the strongest hitter's park effect in the major leagues due to the low air pressure.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] Wrigley Field, home of the Chicago Cubs, is known for its fickle disposition: a pitcher's park when the strong winds off Lake Michigan are blowing in, it becomes more of a hitter's park when they are blowing out.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] The absence of a standardized field affects not only how particular games play out, but the nature of team rosters and players' statistical records.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] For example, hitting a fly ball 330 feet (100 m) into right field might result in an easy catch on the warning track at one park, and a home run at another.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] A team that plays in a park with a relatively short right field, such as the New York Yankees, will tend to stock its roster with left-handed pull hitters, who can best exploit it.
[src:baseball/baseball-p01] On the individual level, a player who spends most of his career with a team that plays in a hitter's park will gain an advantage in batting statistics over time—even more so if his talents are especially suited to the park.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Organized baseball lends itself to statistics to a greater degree than many other sports.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Each play is discrete and has a relatively small number of possible outcomes.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The Official Baseball Rules administered by MLB require the official scorer to categorize each baseball play unambiguously.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The rules provide detailed criteria to promote consistency.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The score report is the official basis for both the box score of the game and the relevant statistical records.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] General managers, managers, and baseball scouts use statistics to evaluate players and make strategic decisions.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Certain traditional statistics are familiar to most baseball fans.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Among the many other statistics that are kept are those collectively known as *situational statistics*.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] For example, statistics can indicate which specific pitchers a certain batter performs best against.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] If a given situation statistically favors a certain batter, the manager of the fielding team may be more likely to change pitchers or have the pitcher intentionally walk the batter in order to face one who is less likely to succeed.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Sabermetrics is the field of baseball statistical study and the development of new statistics and analytical tools.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Such new statistics are also called sabermetrics.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The term was coined around 1980 by one of the field's leading proponents, Bill James, and derives from the Society for American Baseball Research (SABR).
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Writing in 1919, philosopher Morris Raphael Cohen described baseball as the national religion of the US.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In the words of sports columnist Jayson Stark, baseball has long been "a unique paragon of American culture"—a status he sees as devastated by the steroid abuse scandal.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] American influence in the Western Hemisphere has meant that baseball grew significantly in the region.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] A century later, the situation was very different.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] With the rise in popularity of other team sports with much higher average ticket prices—football, basketball, and hockey—professional baseball had become among the most popular blue-collar-oriented American spectator sports.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Overall, baseball has a large following in the United States; a 2006 poll found that nearly half of Americans are fans.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] This led to baseball being granted the title of "America's favorite pastime" by many American baseball fans.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] As historians and scholars now speculate, baseball is a metaphor of the American way of life In the late 1900s and early 2000s, baseball's position compared to football in the United States moved in contradictory directions.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In 2008, MLB set a revenue record of $6.5 billion, matching the NFL's revenue for the first time in decades.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] A new MLB revenue record of more than $10 billion was set in 2017.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] On the other hand, the percentage of American sports fans polled who named baseball as their favorite sport was 9%, compared to pro football at 37%.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In 1985, the respective figures were pro football 24%, baseball 23%.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Because there are so many more major league games played, there is no comparison in overall attendance.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In 2008, total attendance at major league games was the second-highest in history: 78.6 million, 0.7% off the record set the previous year.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The following year, amid the U.S. recession, attendance fell by 6.6% to 73.4 million.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Eight years later, it dropped under 73 million.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Attendance at games held under the Minor League Baseball umbrella set a record in 2008, with 43.3 million.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] While MLB games have not drawn the same national TV viewership as football games, MLB games are dominant in teams' local markets and regularly lead all programs in primetime in their markets during the summer.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] After multiple years of declines since 2017, baseball attendance has grown slightly in recent years.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In 2024, attendance was 71.3 million, the highest since 2017.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball is very popular in Venezuela; in 2011, 95% of people surveyed claimed it to be the national sport.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In Nicaragua and Panama, baseball is also considered the national sport.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] While soccer is still more popular, baseball is a fast-growing sport in Mexico.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In 2024, top Mexican League baseball teams outdraw some Liga MX teams in attendance.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball also is somewhat popular in Colombia, though secondary to soccer, especially in coastal areas such as Barranquilla and Cartagena which are near the Caribbean.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In recent years, baseball has grown in popularity in Colombia, especially in the capital of Bogotá, due an increase of Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In Brazil, baseball fan popularity has grown in the last few years, thanks to MLB broadcasts in Brazilian ESPN and the historic silver medal in 2023 Pan-American games.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] However, it still lags behind basketball and American football in the list of most played sports in Brazil.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball has also grown in popularity in Argentina and Peru in recent years due to Venezuelan immigrants.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Costa Rica has also seen a growth in the popularity of baseball.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Since 1987, baseballs have exclusively been made in the Costa Rican town of Turrialba.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In recent years, Major leaguer Mauricio Dubón has made efforts to increase support for the sport in the country.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The sport's overall popularity in Latin America has assisted in integrating Latin American migrants to the United States.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Since the early 1980s, the Dominican Republic, in particular the city of San Pedro de Macorís, has been the major leagues' primary source of foreign talent.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In 2017, 83 of the 868 players on MLB Opening Day rosters (and disabled lists) were from the country.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Among other Caribbean countries and territories, a combined 97 MLB players were born in Venezuela, Cuba, and Puerto Rico.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Hall-of-Famer Roberto Clemente remains one of the greatest national heroes in Puerto Rico's history.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] While baseball has long been the island's primary athletic pastime, its once well-attended professional winter league has declined in popularity since 1990, when young Puerto Rican players began to be included in the major leagues' annual first-year player draft.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In Cuba, where baseball is by every reckoning the national sport, the national team overshadows the city and provincial teams that play in the top-level domestic leagues.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball is also one of the most popular sports of Aruba and Curaçao, and a growing sport in The Bahamas and the US Virgin Islands.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In East Asia, baseball is among the most popular sports in Japan, Taiwan and South Korea.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In Japan, where baseball is inarguably the leading spectator team sport, combined revenue for the twelve teams in Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB), the body that oversees both the Central and Pacific Leagues, was estimated at $1 billion in 2007.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Total NPB attendance for the year was approximately 20 million.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] While in the preceding two decades, MLB attendance grew by 50 percent and revenue nearly tripled, the comparable NPB figures were stagnant.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] There are concerns that MLB's growing interest in acquiring star Japanese players will hurt the game in their home country.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Revenue figures are not released for the country's amateur system.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Similarly, according to one official pronouncement, the sport's governing authority "has never taken into account attendance ... because its greatest interest has always been the development of athletes".
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In Taiwan, baseball is one of the most widely spectated sports, in TV and person.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown significantly in China in recent years, with MLB estimating in 2019 that there are 21 million active fans in the country.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball was considered a national pastime in the Philippines in the 1960s and 70s, but the sport has since declined in popularity.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Since 2005, there have been efforts to revitalize the sport in the country.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball saw a surge in popularity in Thailand following the countries' silver medal in baseball in the 2025 SEA Games, which were hosted in Thailand.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball is generally a niche sport in Europe.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] However, baseball is somewhat popular in the Netherlands, where it is known as *honkbal*, thanks to influence from the United States after World War II and the Kingdoms control over Aruba and Curaçao where it is the most popular sport.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball is also somewhat popular in portions of Italy, especially in the town of Nettuno, due to influence from American soldiers after World War II.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball has grown in recent years in the Czech Republic, due in part to the Czech teams' success in the 2023 World Baseball Classic.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball is one of the most popular sports in Palau and Guam.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In Australia, baseball is a niche sport but the country does have a professional league.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Because the league is played in winter for the western hemisphere, it attracts American and Korean professional players looking to play winter league baseball.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In 2026, there were more than 30 Australians playing college baseball in the United States compared to six in 2020.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The Dodgers operate a large baseball academy in Mpigi, Uganda, and there are also baseball programs in Luwero, Uganda.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] There is also a Africa Baseball Academy in Nairobi, Nigeria.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball was popular in South Africa prior to World War 2 but popularity has since waned.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] There are still teams and attempts to raise the popularity of baseball in the country, including the introduction of Baseball5.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] There is a growing baseball program in South Sudan, which has resulted in professional contracts.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The Japan-Africa Baseball & Softball Foundation has created Koshien high school baseball tournaments in Tanzania, Ghana and Kenya, which Tanzania being the most successful.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] There are further plans for similar tournaments in Nigeria, South Sudan, Benin, Cameroon and Zambia.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] As of 2024, Little League Baseball oversees leagues with 2 million participants in more than 80 countries.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The number of players has fallen since the 1990s, when 3 million children took part in Little League Baseball annually.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Babe Ruth League teams have over 1 million participants.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] According to the president of the International Baseball Federation in 2009, between 300,000 and 500,000 women and girls play baseball around the world, including Little League and the introductory game of Tee Ball.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] A varsity baseball team is an established part of physical education departments at most high schools and colleges in the United States.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In 2015, nearly half a million high schoolers and over 34,000 collegians played on their schools' baseball teams.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] By early in the 20th century, intercollegiate baseball was Japan's leading sport.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Today, high school baseball in particular is immensely popular there.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The final rounds of the two annual tournaments—the National High School Baseball Invitational Tournament in the spring, and the even more important National High School Baseball Championship in the summer—are broadcast around the country.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The tournaments are known, respectively, as Spring Koshien and Summer Koshien after the 55,000-capacity stadium where they are played.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In Cuba, baseball is a mandatory part of the state system of physical education, which begins at age six.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Talented children as young as seven are sent to special district schools for more intensive training—the first step on a ladder whose acme is the national baseball team.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball has had a broad impact on popular culture, both in the United States and elsewhere.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Dozens of English-language idioms have been derived from baseball; in particular, the game is the source of a number of widely used sexual euphemisms.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The first networked radio broadcasts in North America were of the 1922 World Series: famed sportswriter Grantland Rice announced play-by-play from New York City's Polo Grounds on WJZ–Newark, New Jersey, which was connected by wire to WGY–Schenectady, New York, and WBZ–Springfield, Massachusetts.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The baseball cap has become a ubiquitous fashion item not only in the United States and Japan, but also in countries where the sport itself is not particularly popular, such as the United Kingdom.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball has inspired many works of art and entertainment.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] There have been many baseball movies, including the Academy Award–winning *The Pride of the Yankees* (1942) and the Oscar nominees *The Natural* (1984) and *Field of Dreams* (1989).
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The American Film Institute's selection of the ten best sports movies includes *The Pride of the Yankees* at number 3 and *Bull Durham* (1988) at number 5.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball has provided thematic material for hits on both stage—the Adler–Ross musical *Damn Yankees*—and record—George J.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Gaskin's "Slide, Kelly, Slide", Simon and Garfunkel's "Mrs.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Robinson", and John Fogerty's "Centerfield".
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The baseball-inspired comedic sketch "Who's on First?", popularized by Abbott and Costello in 1938, quickly became famous; six decades later, *Time* named it the best comedy routine of the 20th century.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Literary works connected to the game include the short fiction of Ring Lardner and novels such as Bernard Malamud's *The Natural* (the source for the movie), Robert Coover's *The Universal Baseball Association, Inc., J.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Henry Waugh, Prop.*, John Grisham's Calico Joe and W.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Kinsella's *Shoeless Joe* (the source for *Field of Dreams*).
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball's literary canon also includes the beat reportage of Damon Runyon; the columns of Grantland Rice, Red Smith, Dick Young, and Peter Gammons; and the essays of Roger Angell.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Among the celebrated nonfiction books in the field are Lawrence S.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Ritter's *The Glory of Their Times*, Roger Kahn's *The Boys of Summer*, and Michael Lewis's *Moneyball*.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The 1970 publication of major league pitcher Jim Bouton's tell-all chronicle *Ball Four* is considered a turning point in the reporting of professional sports.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball has also inspired the creation of new cultural forms.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball cards were introduced in the late 19th century as trade cards.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] A typical example featured an image of a baseball player on one side and advertising for a business on the other.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In the early 1900s they were produced widely as promotional items by tobacco and confectionery companies.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The 1930s saw the popularization of the modern style of baseball card, with a player photograph accompanied on the rear by statistics and biographical data.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Baseball cards—many of which are now prized collectibles—are the source of the much broader trading card industry, involving similar products for different sports and non-sports-related fields.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Modern fantasy sports began in 1980 with the invention of Rotisserie League Baseball by New York writer Daniel Okrent and several friends.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Participants in a Rotisserie league draft notional teams from the list of active MLB players and play out an entire imaginary season with game outcomes based on the players' latest real-world statistics.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Rotisserie-style play quickly became a phenomenon.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Now known more generically as fantasy baseball, it has inspired similar games based on an array of different sports.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The field boomed with increasing Internet access and new fantasy sports-related websites.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] By 2008, 29.9 million people in the United States and Canada were playing fantasy sports, spending $800 million on the hobby.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The burgeoning popularity of fantasy baseball is also credited with the increasing attention paid to sabermetrics—first among fans, only later among baseball professionals.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Informal variations of baseball have popped up over time, with games like corkball reflecting local traditions and allowing the game to be played in diverse environments.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Two variations of baseball, softball and Baseball5, are internationally governed alongside baseball by the World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] American professional baseball teams toured Britain in 1874 and 1889, and had a great effect on similar sports in Britain.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] In Wales and Merseyside, a strong community game had already developed with skills and plays more in keeping with the American game and the Welsh began to informally adopt the name "baseball" (Pêl Fas), to reflect the American style.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] By the 1890s, calls were made to follow the success of other working class sports (like Rugby in Wales and Soccer in Merseyside) and adopt a distinct set of rules and bureaucracy.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] During the 1892 season rules for the game of "baseball" were agreed and the game was officially codified.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] Finnish baseball, also known as pesäpallo, is a combination of traditional ball-batting team games and North American baseball, invented by Lauri "Tahko" Pihkala in the 1920s.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] The basic idea of pesäpallo is similar to that of baseball: the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] One of the most important differences between pesäpallo and baseball is that the ball is pitched vertically, which makes hitting the ball, as well as controlling the power and direction of the hit, much easier.
[src:baseball/baseball-p02] This gives the offensive game more variety, speed, and tactical aspects compared to baseball.
